by Alliance of Self-Defensive Territories » Sat Sep 04, 2021 7:50 am

Wormfodder Delivery wrote:
Dexterra wrote:My socialist self has noticed a ton of corporatocracies and other big business-run nations, especially here on F7

I personally see the opposite.
The number of mega corporations is far outstripped by the number of communist nations.

I personally think that has to do with the fact Communism is an ideology where as traditionally "corporate-run" nations (Not OTL US-tier, like, "the status of CEO and President are the same" tier) do not exist.

With the former, there's a lot to draw on historically-speaking which allows for a much more wider arrange of styles and inspirations, along with being an ideology which in theory means that it can be molded to whatever the author wants. (People who consider themselves "communists" range from Hardcore Stalinists bordering on Fascism to Democratic Socialists bordering on being Social Democrats)

Meanwhile, a corporatocracy has only seen examples in the form of Colonial Companies like the Honourable East India Company. Which are A) PT, B) Usually backed by an empire, and C) Are unstable and usually lead to the government they represent annexing the region after only a few decades - maybe a century at most. So a person who doesn't want to create a colonial empire but wants to have fun with a meme-tier dictatorship run by Elon Musk is... very limited on things to draw upon. Not to mention - we all know what a corporate nation would focus on: The Bottom Line. While there may be variation in how they get profit, a corporation will always do whatever they need to do to make the most short-term profit as possible - leaving very little room for ideological struggle, factionalism, etc. Which, I am pretty sure would get boring after awhile unless you're a god-tier worldbuilder like Synne Industries (which funnily enough, is an example of a corporate-themed nation being really, really amazing in terms of worldbuilding.)

I did try to dabble in it myself with a nation called "Yaiona'ni", which was a late PMT/Early FT nation which got shafted out of colonizing other planets and so became the Galaxy's Bazaar instead. But honestly, I just felt like my priorities were scattered and had no real narrative behind it outside of "hey look, funny lizard people with money."

Great for the guy on top, not great for the everyone else whose suffering from brain drain because all the smart and talented people keep getting cancelled/murdered.

The fact that the opening post basically set up the entire situation as "okay so we wiped out everything anyways, thanks for reading" didn't help to draw any kind of incentive to actually interact, given there really isn't any reason TO interact much less drop a post of "oh, okay, so I, [country], send support to combat the invaders/aid the invaders to stake a claim for myself."

Also to extend upon this, there's no point in FT roleplays to use planet-killing weapons. Again, a huge waste of resources that can't even pay itself off given a lack of return. Now, glassing a planet? That offers some return in raw materials salvaged from the planet and could even pay off such a weapon. Ditto for any other method of erasing or eradicating life on a foreign celestial body without actually DESTROYING it.
